Paule,

This exception indicates that you have an error in your test.  Tests that run in "quick mode" but fail in standard mode are a common class of problems that often involve the state of the system under test.  Building resilient AGR tests is sometimes difficult, and sometimes requires workarounds, but in my experience (at least), it can be done and is worthwhile.

Moving forwward, I suggest you record a simple testcase that makes no assumptions about the state of the workbench (clicks on the File menu, for instance) and add it as the only invocation in your behavior.  Then verify that it runs correctly in standard mode.  Then you can try to create more involved actions and continue adding them to the behavior.  If something fails with a macro error in standard mode, this means you need to debug your test to try to infer why it is failing and correct the macro, either by editing, re-recording or changing the way you are accomplishing your task.  

Note that the exception provided by TPTP tells you the line number of the error in your macro.  In the exception you pasted, it shows the following information:  MacroCommand [item-expand, line 91].  This is line 91 of your macro, which is trying to expand an element called "package1.bmes".  It would appear that this element does not exist when your test is running in standard mode (perhaps because the project you're using is different in your runtime shell than the one you have in your development workbench.)  As an aside, most of us record our tests to set up the workspace as part of our tests (for example, importing an existing project as the first test case in our behavior.)  You can then run this same action in quick mode to be sure you have the same project contents for your test to operate on.

I hope this helps.  Thanks for your interest in TPTP.
